RABIES, BOVINE - MEXICO: (TABASCO)
**********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Sun 16 May 2010
Source: El Heraldo de Tabasco [in Spanish, trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
<http://www.oem.com.mx/elheraldodetabasco/notas/n1636005.htm>


Known as paralytic rabies or 'derriengue', cattle farmers from Perla
de la Chontalpa [popular name for the municipality of Comalcalco]
fear for the terrible disease that is causing death among their
herds, and even say it is difficult to cope with the disease due to
the high cost of inputs required to counteract the disease.

In this regard, the president of the Regional Livestock Associations,
Juan Daniel Chavez, said it is hard to determine where the disease is
originating because they [Perla de la Chontalpa] are connected by a
large road to the communities of Paraiso, Cunduacan, and Cardenas,
and the situation negatively affects the producers in general.

He said that health authorities focused medical attention on 3 people
from the cattle farms who had contact with livestock that tested
positive for bovine paralytic rabies according to a diagnosis.

Municipal authorities confirmed that at least 10 of 12 animals tested
positive for the disease and therefore urgently implemented a
vaccination campaign to prevent paralytic rabies among the more than
1600 local cattle farmers.

He mentioned that apart from this locality, [he] is aware that the
federal government is implementing vaccination programs throughout the state.

Paralytic rabies is transmitted by a bat, according to data from the
Sedafot [Secretariat for Agricultural and Forestry Development]. A
practice called "trapping" which consists of trapping some species of
the vampire bat and adding an ointment (Vampiret) on the body, so
that the bat will bring it to the caves or nests [of the bats] and
infect the rest of the animals so they will then die. [They groom the
anticoagulant off of each other. - Mod.TG]

He added that close to 10 000 [doses of] the vaccine called
"Alurabiffa", which costs MXN 2.50 [USD 0.20], have been distributed
among the producers for them to vaccinate their livestock.

In an interview MVZ [veterinarian] Donato Alvarez Heredia explained
that rabies encephalitis is caused by a Rhabdovirus and it affects
all warm-blooded animals. The transmission [of rabies] is through
bites from other animals that have the virus in their saliva. In
cattle the most significant agent is the vampire bat, called
_Desmodus rotundus_, followed by the dog. The disease can also be
spread by wild animals such as foxes, raccoons, and some cats.

Finally, he said that when "we suspect an outbreak of rabies, no one
should touch these animals. And if there are personnel to remove the
brain for laboratory examination, they must wear gloves, and the job
should be done with great care, because if during the work [for
example,] they get saliva in their eye(s), they must be vaccinated.
[Hopefully these workers wear eye protection or preferably a face
shield. - Mod.TG]

In cattle, the incubation period ranges from 25 to more than 150
days. And, while the duration of illness is usually 2-5 days, it may
extend to 8-10 days, and we must say that just from the signs we
cannot distinguish whether the rabies came from a dog or a vampire bite.

[Byline: Olivia Alaniz]

